<methodology slug="product-development-trends">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>researcher</domain>
    <summary>Research lens for current product-development practice trends with URL-cited primary sources using a three-stage pipeline.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>trends</tag>
      <tag>product-development</tag>
      <tag>market-research</tag>
      <tag>methodology</tag>
      <tag>discovery</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Product Development Trends</title>
    <summary>A research lens for current product-development practice trends: AI-augmented ideation, continuous customer feedback loops, rapid-pivot cadence, and cross-functional team structures. Produces a trend brief with URL-cited primary sources. This is the general (non-year-pinned) version; for 2026-specific signal collection and scoring, use product-development-trends-2026 instead.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Development teams misalign on methodology when they use 2019-era playbooks in a 2025+ market. This methodology surfaces the four axes where practice has shifted most, applies a three-stage pipeline (signal collection → triage → human checkpoint), and enforces a recency gate so the brief reflects the current landscape rather than training-data residue.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quarterly methodology alignment before opening the SDD roadmap or spec.</item>
        <item>Briefing a new PM, researcher, or engineer on current team-shape and discovery cadence norms.</item>
        <item>Pre-PRD discovery: surfacing AI-augmented ideation candidates before locking feature specs.</item>
        <item>Competitive briefs where a methodology upgrade is the differentiator (e.g. agile → continuous discovery).</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Sprint planning or story splitting — use pm-agile or sdd-planning instead.</item>
        <item>Single-feature validation — use user-researcher/problem-validation.</item>
        <item>Pricing or TAM/SAM/SOM analysis — use market-researcher/pricing-research and tam-sam-som.</item>
        <item>Less than 6 weeks since last trend pass with no triggering event (funding round, major competitor move, regulatory shift).</item>
        <item>Regulated domains (medical devices, fintech, avionics) where waterfall + audit trail is a contractual requirement.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="trend-axes">
      <rule>
        <statement>Anchor every trend claim to a primary source with a publication date no older than 90 days. Reject any claim without a URL.</statement>
        <rationale>Trend reports decay fast. LLM training data is structurally behind real markets. Consumer behavior trends degrade in months; process trends degrade in one to two years.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>AI-augmented ideation — AI scans market data and surfaces weak signals; humans decide which signals are actionable. Enables pattern recognition at scale that would take weeks manually.</item>
        <item>Continuous customer feedback — real-time iteration loops replacing fixed quarterly research cycles. Reduces the time between hypothesis and evidence.</item>
        <item>Rapid pivots — quarterly adjustment cadence vs annual planning cycles. Lower cost of being wrong; faster response to competitive and market signals.</item>
        <item>Cross-functional teams — PM, Design, and Engineering co-owning discovery and delivery. Reduces handoff latency and aligns accountability with outcomes.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="key-research-output-types">
      <p>Trend research produces four types of artifacts for downstream consumption:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Market Analysis Reports — size, trends, competitive landscape with sourced figures</item>
        <item>User Need Assessments — pain points and unmet needs with source citations and frequency counts</item>
        <item>Concept Validation Studies — evidence that an idea has a real market before engineering begins</item>
        <item>Feature Priority Reports — ranked list of what to build first, based on evidence strength and segment fit</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="separation-rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep process trends (how teams work) and consumer trends (what users want) in separate sections. Never mix them in a single bullet list.</statement>
        <rationale>Mixed trend lists prevent teams from routing insights to the right function. Process trends drive team-shape and tooling decisions; consumer trends drive feature and positioning decisions. Mixing produces unfocused roadmap inputs.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="three-stage-pipeline">
      <p>Stage 1 (sonnet-class, broad): WebSearch + WebFetch across trend axes, collect raw signals. Stage 2 (opus-class, synthesis): score each signal on recency, evidence, and applicability; emit ranked table. Stage 3 (human checkpoint): accept or reject claims before they land in .aidocs/product_docs/trend-report.md.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>The human checkpoint before writing to .aidocs/ is mandatory. Hallucinated tool names or vendor capabilities must not reach deliverables.</statement>
        <rationale>Trend deliverables shape roadmap conversations. A hallucinated vendor capability or unsourced claim landing in a product brief costs more to correct downstream than the checkpoint costs upfront.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="signal-scoring">
      <p>Three scoring dimensions, each 0-3, threshold for inclusion: total >= 5.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Recency: 3 = within 30 days, 2 = 31-90 days, 1 = 91-180 days, 0 = older than 180 days</item>
        <item>Evidence: 3 = primary source, 2 = 3+ independent citations, 1 = secondary aggregator</item>
        <item>Applicability: 0-3 set by human reviewer based on fit to this specific product</item>
      </list>
      <reference path="templates/score-signals.py">Signal scoring script with threshold filtering and markdown table output</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="audit-trail">
      <rule>
        <statement>Persist raw signals to .aidocs/research/raw/signals.jsonl. The diff between this quarter and the previous file is more useful than the polished narrative.</statement>
        <rationale>The trend delta — what is new, what faded, what reversed — is the real finding. Without a persistent artifact, each quarterly run starts from scratch and misses the directional signal.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Include a "kill list": for every trend adopted, name one prior practice stopped. Trend reports without subtractions are theatre.</statement>
        <rationale>Additive-only trend reports imply infinite capacity. A kill list forces a real trade-off and signals to the team that the methodology acknowledges opportunity cost.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-failure-modes">
      <p>Trend reports decay fast: anything older than 90 days is suspect for "consumer behavior" claims; LLM training data is structurally behind real markets.</p>
      <p>Survivorship bias in trend articles — "AI-augmented ideation" gets cited because it's loud, not because it ships outcomes; demand a concrete shipped-vs-killed ratio.</p>
      <p>Confounds correlation with causation (cross-functional teams "cause" speed). Without a control case, treat as hypothesis, not finding.</p>
      <p>LLMs hallucinate vendor capabilities and pricing. Every tool/SaaS claim must be re-verified with WebFetch on the vendor's own page before publishing.</p>
      <p>"Days, not weeks" turnaround is aspirational for regulated domains (fintech, health, gov) — call out where the trend does not apply.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Drive trend research as a three-stage pipeline: (1) signal collection by a sonnet-class subagent doing wide WebSearch + WebFetch; (2) signal triage and synthesis by an opus-class subagent that scores each signal on recency × evidence × applicability; (3) human checkpoint to accept/reject claims before they are written into .aidocs/product_docs/trend-report.md. Inside this repo, route via faion-research-agent (mode ideas or market) and let it spawn the per-signal sub-tasks. Persist the raw signal log under .aidocs/research/raw/ so subsequent quarters can diff against it instead of re-scraping.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Anchor every macro trend to one internal data point from your own product analytics; if you cannot, downgrade the trend to "watch list" not "act".</item>
        <item>Force a "kill list": for every trend you adopt, name one current practice you stop. Trend reports without subtractions are theatre.</item>
        <item>Separate "consumer trends" (slow, demographic) from "platform trends" (fast, technology). Mixing them in one bucket is the most common failure mode.</item>
        <item>Date-stamp every claim at the bullet level, not just the document. Future agents diff bullet-dates to detect staleness.</item>
        <item>Keep a signals.jsonl audit trail. The diff between this quarter's and last quarter's file is more useful than the polished narrative.</item>
        <item>For AI-augmented ideation specifically: log the human override rate. If humans accept &gt;90% of LLM-surfaced ideas, the LLM is not ideating — it is rubber-stamping. If &lt;10%, the prompt is broken.</item>
        <item>Cap each trend at 3 sentences in the executive summary. Long entries always indicate weak evidence padding.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Over-indexing on US/SF Bay Area sources without requiring EU or APAC primary sources.</description>
        <reason>LLMs are trained on US-centric data. Force at least one EU and one APAC primary source per trend or the brief is regionally biased.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using raw WebSearch results ranked by SEO rather than by publication date.</description>
        <reason>SEO-optimised blog spam ranks above primary research. Always sort by published date in your scraper before summarizing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>"Rapid pivots, quarterly cycles" assertions without named organizations or concrete shipping evidence.</description>
        <reason>This is a popular LLM completion regardless of evidence. Treat any unsourced cadence claim as hallucinated.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cross-functional team claims usually cite the same 2–3 secondary sources (HBR, McKinsey blog) as independent evidence.</description>
        <reason>Do not let three citations to the same article inflate confidence.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Missing human-in-the-loop checkpoint before writing into .aidocs/product_docs/.</description>
        <reason>A human must accept the final scored signal table. Without this gate, hallucinated tool/vendor names land in deliverables.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-subagents">
      <list>
        <item>faion-research-agent — orchestrator; switch to mode ideas for ideation trends, market for adoption/competitive trends, pricing for monetization trends.</item>
        <item>faion-domain-checker-agent — when trends spawn product-naming candidates, verify availability before they leak into a deck.</item>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — only after the trend report is ratified; converts accepted trend implications into backlog/ features.</item>
        <item>password-scrubber-agent — run before publishing if WebFetch surfaced API keys or session tokens in raw signal dumps.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="recommended-tools">
      <list>
        <item>crawl4ai or trafilatura — LLM-friendly site-to-markdown for trend article ingestion</item>
        <item>pytrends — Unofficial Google Trends API, validates "rising" claims with search volume</item>
        <item>gh (GitHub CLI) — Mine release notes, issue trends, "awesome-X" curation</item>
        <item>jq — Slice signal JSONL piles fed to the synthesis agent</item>
        <item>ddgr — Anonymous DuckDuckGo search to cross-check WebSearch results</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="signal-scoring-example">
      <p>Each signal is scored on three dimensions (max 9 points). Score each signal on three dimensions: recency (3 = within 30 days, 2 = 31-90 days, 1 = 91-180 days, 0 = older), evidence (3 = primary source, 2 = 3+ independent citations, 1 = secondary aggregator), applicability (0-3 assigned by human based on fit). Drop any signal with total score below 5.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="when-routing-features">
      <rule>
        <statement>When the methodology spawns SDD features, route them through faion-sdd-executor-agent with explicit acceptance criteria — "act on trend X" is not a feature.</statement>
        <rationale>Without explicit acceptance criteria, trend-to-feature translation produces vague tickets that no one can implement or verify.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Cost control: synthesis stage on opus with 50+ signals can exceed 100k tokens. Pre-filter with the signal scoring script before synthesis to keep costs proportionate to delivered value.</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/score-signals.py" purpose="Signal scoring: recency/evidence/applicability scoring, threshold filtering, markdown table output"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
